{"award_age":80.0,"bio_image":"full\/c8957dcdc44816b6737bb14e33049878e7d2596b.jpg","category":"Physics","country":"United States","date_of_birth":"1925-09-01T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":null,"gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/7\/75\/Roy_Glauber_Dec_10_2005.jpg\/200px-Roy_Glauber_Dec_10_2005.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Roy_J._Glauber","mini_bio":"<p><b>Roy Jay Glauber<\/b> (born September 1, 1925) is an American theoretical <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Physicist\" title=\"Physicist\">physicist<\/a>. He is the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Mallinckrodt\" title=\"Mallinckrodt\">Mallinckrodt<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Professor\" title=\"Professor\">Professor<\/a> of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Physics\" title=\"Physics\">Physics<\/a> at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Harvard_University\" title=\"Harvard University\">Harvard University<\/a> and Adjunct Professor of Optical Sciences at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/University_of_Arizona\" title=\"University of Arizona\">University of Arizona<\/a>. Born in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/New_York_City\" title=\"New York City\">New York City<\/a>, he was awarded one half of the 2005 <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Physics\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Physics\">Nobel Prize in Physics<\/a> \"for his contribution to the quantum theory of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Coherence_(physics)\" title=\"Coherence (physics)\">optical coherence<\/a>\", with the other half shared by <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/John_L._Hall\" title=\"John L. Hall\">John L. Hall<\/a> and <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Theodor_W._H%C3%A4nsch\" title=\"Theodor W. H\u00e4nsch\">Theodor W. H\u00e4nsch<\/a>. In this work, published in 1963, he created a model for <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Photodetection\" title=\"Photodetection\">photodetection<\/a> and explained the fundamental characteristics of different types of light, such as <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Laser\" title=\"Laser\">laser<\/a> light (see <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Coherent_state\" title=\"Coherent state\" class=\"mw-redirect\">coherent state<\/a>) and light from light bulbs (see <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Blackbody\" title=\"Blackbody\" class=\"mw-redirect\">blackbody<\/a>). His theories are widely used in the field of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Quantum_optics\" title=\"Quantum optics\">quantum optics<\/a>.<\/p>","name":"Roy J. Glauber","place_of_birth":"New York City ,  New York ,  U.S.","place_of_death":null,"text":"Roy J. Glauber , Physics, 2005","year":2005.0}